{"/service/ndnp/vi/batch_vi_fortis_ver01/data/sn85034357/0054286705A/1930080801/0524.xml":{"full_text":"I\nClinch Valley News\nESTABLISHED 1845.\nEntered at the Tazewell, (Va.), post\noffice as second class mail matter\nunder act of Congress.\nJ. A. LESLIE SON, Publisher*\nTERMS OF SUBSCRIPTION\n(In Advance.)\nBy mail, postpaid, one year,-$1.50\nFRIDAY, AUGUST 8, 1930.\nMILK.\nAn estimate of the monthly re\nceipts from the sale of' milk in Taze\nwell county, an industry still in its\nswaddling clothes, is from eighteen to\ntwenty thousand dollars. This is one\nof the bright spots and an industry\nthat will eventually revolutionize the\nfarming and cattle business of Taze\nwell county. The cattle business has\nalways been a speculative one, but the\nmilk business, although the returns\nunder some conditions may not appear\ncommensurate with the amount of la\nbor put forth, can nearly always be\ndepended upon to bring in a good re\nturn under all conditions. A number\nof graziers of the county realize this\nsituation and are governing them\nselves accordingly. Few of the big\nestates can be adjusted to dairying\naltogether, but the prediction is free\nly made that many of the larger cat\ntle men of the county will in the very\nnear future give some attention, at\nleast, to the milk business.\nEverybody realizes that one of the\ndraw-backs to the milk business is\nthe work attached to it, but in this\nmechanical age machinery is avail\nable that will remove the drudgery of\ndairying, solve the labor problem and\nmake the business profitable and\nworth while.\nYou don\u2019t hear of much poverty\nand misery in the Clear Fork section\nof the county due to the milk busi\nness that has developed there in the\nlast few years and the industrious\nand hustling spirit of its people.\nTHE STORM IS PASSING.\nThere are many indications that\nthe business outlook is brighter now\nand getting more so each day, espec\nially in the coal industry. A well\nknown coal operator, familiar with\nthe situation, has suggested that by\nearly frost coal will be moving and\nbusiness generally will be in better\nshape. He states that, the factories of\nthe South and the New England\nStates have been shipping from the\nwarehouses for several months; that\nthe coal yards of the country have no\nsurplus coal, and that the dry weath\ner has forced many utility compan\nies to resort to steam in place of wa\nter power. The shipments to the\nnorthwest, known as the lake trade,\nhave not yet started in earnest, and\nthat all these things consdeired, there\nseems to be every prospect of unusu\nal activity in the coal industry this\nfall.\nThis is certainly a very optimistic\nview of the situation and one that\nwill certainly help drive away the\ngloom that has settled over this sec\ntion.\nTHE DINNER PAIL.\nHon. Mr. Shaffer will soon open his\ndefensive campaign in the Ninth dis\ntrict, and there are a whole lot of\nthings the voters would like to know\nabout. Joe had better tell jokes and\nabuse the Virginia election laws, and\nlay off Hoover prosperity. Don\u2019t men\ntion national politics in the Ninth dis\ntrict or there might be a riot.\nDROUGHT CONDITIONS\nThe following headline appeared in\nthe Cincinnati Enquirer, evening of\nAug. 5th, indicative of drouth condit\nions in Ohio and other States:\nCrops ruined\u2014Death toll heavy\u2014\nMercury near top of the tube\u2014Farm\nanimals suffer for water\u2014Cotton\nfields in worse condition in years\u2014\nLife in cities likened to that in trop\nics\u2014Damage to crops estimated at\n400 million dollars.\nA plauge of grasshoppers advanc\ning on border of Texas from Mexico\nthreatens destruction to cotton and\nother crops already seriously injured\nby the drought. Streaims, rivers and\nwells throughout the whole Midwest\nhave become dusty. Fish are report\ned dying by the thousands. Added to\nravages of the drough fire is raging\nin a number of sections of Ohio and\nWest Virginia.\nARE?\nWe stated to a man froun Buchanan!\ncounty the other day that business\nwas better and a brighter day was\nnot far ahead. This soaked into his\nsystem by the time he got home, and\nhe sat down and wrote us as follows:\n\u201cYou are a liar and truth is not in\nyou. Save me a place in the poor\nhouse; we are going to need it as\nsure as the big fish still lives.\u201d\nSTONE MOUNTAIN MEMORIAL.\nAfter turmoil and trouble and a!\nlong interim of silence and uncer\ntainty, the dispatch from Atlanta\nindicates that work will be resumed\non the memorial. Admitting that the\nwonderful undertaking was justifiable\nin the first place, it is sincerely hoped\nthat the work now go forward to\ncompletion. _\nt\nTHE DROUGHT STILL HOLDS.\nThe destruction and ruin to crops is\nabout completed in many sections.\nThe pasture lands are bare. The corn\nand vegetables are withering and dy\ning. The statement is made that the\nfish in the streams and rivers of the'\neast and elsewhere are dying on ac-!\ncount of low waters.\nApple orchards show the effects of\nthe protracted dry weather. The mer- j\ncury has ranged from 80 to 100 de-\u2018\ngrees and over\u2014as high as 114 in\nmany states in the Midwest and\nSouthwest. Copious continued rains atj\nonce, it is thought, would partially\nrelieve the situation. j\nToo Hot To Write Editorials.\u2014\nHeadline. Call it hot now, but just\nwait until John Flannagan and Joe\nShaffer unlimber, and watch the mer\ncury!\nThe special and regular session of\nthe 71st Congress, wfhieh has just\nadjourned, enacted 927 laws and\nSenator Fess is preparing to claim\nevery single one of them as an out\nstanding achievement and national\ntriumph tor the Hoover administra\ntion.\n\nThe Hoover administration will go\ndown into history as the Five-Billion\nDollar-a-Year administration.\nPOLITICS AND PERSONALITIES.\nLast year at this time spectators\nwere hailing the Democratic party\u2019s\n\u201ccomeback.\u201d Now they are cheering\nwith equal vigor the announced in\ntention of the Republicans to stage a\ncomeback of their own.\nCertainly the Democrats have every\ncard in their hands right now. It is\nan \u201coff year,\u201d a factor that has al\nmost invariably proved fortunate for\ntheir minority party. The tariff steal,\nthe Farm Board\u2019s failure, the sudden\nvanishing of the \u201cfull dinner pail,\u201d\nand the prevailing unemployment\nmake anfmunition for congressional\ncampaign. Democrats are predicting a\nsubstantial majority in thee IIous\nand a possible majority even in the\nSenate.\nThe most spectacular fights will\ncenter around senatorial primaries\nand general election-. In the \u201csolid\nsouth\u201d there is little danger of any\nRepublican making the grade. But if\nJoe Robinson of Arkansas, who is lac\ning stiff opposition, should be defeat\ned, a Democratic presidential candi\ndate might be lost to the country. Al\nthough Alabama will undoubtedly re\nturn a Democrat, Tom Heflin\u2019s cam\npaign is drawing nation-wide atten\ntion. Pat Ilarrisson of Mississippi will\nhave to fight for his seat, but he has\nslight cause for worry.\nOut in Illinois, \u201cJim Ham\u201d Lewis\nand Ruth Hanna McCormick are beat\ning their drums to battle in pictures\nque fashion. In Montana the brilliant\nThomas J. Walsh is putting up a gajne\nfight against a popular and powerful\njudge in his state. The odds are heav\nily against Senator Daniel Steck, Iowa\nDemocrat, who seems likely to go\ndown before the Progressive Republi\ncan, Congressman Dickinson, this fall.\nTHE COME BACK.\nForecasts of business revival used\nto be based on many conflicting\ngrounds, but have now arriced at a\ngratifying unanimity. Virtually every\nbody is agreed that a turn for the\nbetter must soon come because we are\nso very far down.\nIndeed, one may encounter optim\nists actually rubbing their hands and\nchuckling at the way production and\nprices are going down. Boy, what a\nboom that will mean some day!\nIn the meantime, every country on\nearth (has been applying the same\nmagic fonmula to stimulate business\nrevival. What can be simpler than\nbuying not a shred from any other\ncountry and selling lots and lots of\nstuff to every other country?\nAs to shoving up the price of\nwheat by Farm Boards and similar\ndevices, Mr. Coolidge was rather fa\nvorable to the experiment early in\nJuly and outspoken against it at the\nend of July. This shows' he is master\ning the secret of writing for a great\nmany newspapers of all shades of\nopinion.\u2014New York Times.\nBELIEVE IT OR NOT.\nThe Virginia farmer wakes up be\nfore daylight by the alarm of a clock\nmade in Connecticut; washes his face\nwith Cincinnati soap in a New Jersey\ntin washpan; builds a fire i na Kala\nmazoo stove to boil Louisiana coffee\nwhich he drinks with his biiscuits\nmade of Minneapolis flour, and Kan\nsas City bacon, also perhaps has\nsome New Orleans molasses. He then\nhitches a Kentucky mule to a South\nBend plow and scratches a farm cov\nered with an Ohio mortgage, copies\nof which are filed in his Shaw-Walk\n\u00aer Executive Safe from Muskegon,\nMichigan. When the day is far spent\nbe returns to his home built of Mis\nsissippi cypress and California shin\ngles; sitting down to a Grand Rapids\ntable covered with a Massachusetts\noilcloth he eats Chicago side meat,\nIllinois corn-pone, Japan tea, flavored\nwith New York condensed milk, and\nsweetened with Cuban sugar. After\nwards he reads by the light of Penn\nsylvania oil in a Pittsburg lamp a\nchapter of the Good Book printed in\nBoston and says a prayer written in\nJerusalmles; he then takes off his\nMichigan overalls. New Hampshire\nshirt, and Missouri boots, and crawls\ninto an Indiana bed and covers him\nself with a New Jersey Blanket, only\nto be kept awake all night by the\nhowling of the family dog which is\nthe only home raised product on the\nplace.\u2014Ex.\nTreaties do not of themselves al\nI worked like a young man in a\ngun factory until I was 104 or 105.\nThen I got a neasier job and went\non working until I was 135\u2014Zaro\nAgha.\nShe Pm from Missouri and you\u2019ve 1\ngot to sho wme. i\n\u2014Well, I\u2019m from Elgin so Just\nwatch. t\nTells About Gandhi\nAnd His Followers\nDafmoh, C. P., India, July 3, 1930.\u2014\nI really do not intend continue writ\ning every week, but I shall tell some\nthing about the situation here, a topic\nwhich came to our attention during\nvacation only through the newspapers.\nAll was quiet in Kashmir; we merely\nsaw a few Gandhi caps and flags.\nOne stand for which I admire Gan\ndhi is that against the caste system.\nHe speaks and works against it, and\npractices what he advises. He adopted\na low caste girl and treats her just\njas a daughter. Another fine belief is\nin the equality of rights for men and\n'women. That is indeed very bad ni\nIndia. He i\u00a7 sincere and frank. We\ncannot understand some beliefs' on\nwhich he puts emphasis. He urges the\nprotection of the cow, that none should\n(be killed for any reason. He thinks\nIthat everything modern should be de\nstroyed and that India should move\nalong as it did before the advent of\nrailways, cars, machinery, etc.; he\nthinks that everything foreign should\nbe banished. The exclusive use of the\nspinning wheel is a symbol of his be\nlief. Of course his most prominent pol\nicy at the present is complete inde\npendence.\nMany people advocate dominion sta\ntus instead of complete independence.1\nBy that they meant the advanced po\nlitical status of Canada. The congress\n(composed of represetnatives of the\nIndians who desire independence for\nIndia) which met in Calcutta in Dec.,\n1928, resolved that unless Dominion\nStatus was granted during the next\nyear, this goal should be definitely\nabandoned in favor of complete inde\npendence. Dominion Status was not\ngranted, but a Round Table Confer\nence was offered by the Viceroy, and\nrepected. An American, Mr. Kirby\nPage, writes: \u201cIt is incomprehensible\nwith the Labor Government in office\nand a sympathetic Viceroy at Delhi,\nihat the offer of a Round Table Con\nference should have been, rejected.\nWhy did they not wait and see what\ncould have been achieved by discus\nsion before resorting to non-coopera\ntion? My personal opinion is that the\nCongress has committed a grave blun\nder. It is unfortunate that the nation\nalist leaders are boycotting the pro\nposed conference and are inaugurat\ning non-cooperation at this stage\nwhen so many of their demands could\nhave been obtained by persuasion and\npatience. I am of the opinion that\nmore rapid and permanent progress\nwould have made if they had been\nwilling to accept a new Dominion\nStatus Constitution which would have\ngiven them complete autonomy within\none or two leaders.\u201d Mr. Page at\ntended the Congress meetings, and in\nthe conversation there heard some of\nthe reasons for \u201cthis apparent precip\nitate and unwise action.\u201d\nAs you know, the first attack in\nGandhi\u2019s campaign was launched\nagainst the salt tax. The salt mono\npoly as it now stands is a recent\nenactment of the British Government,\n(n order to provide extra funds to pay\nBritish officials and the expenses of\nan augmented English garrison, and\nto build \u201ca capital to outrank fin\n1 splendour any in the world.\u201d The gov\nernment doubled the tax on salt. From\nthis tax the British Government in\nIndia gets 4.9 per cent of its revenue.\nIndians were opposed to the icreased\nsalt tax. It is not surprising that the\nfirst attack was against that. Not\nonly have followers of Gandhi made\nsalt locally as an expression of law\nbreaking, but thousands have tried to\ncapture the \u201csalt works,\u201d where salt\nis being made by Government. In\nthese raids many people have been\ninjured and arrests have been made\nIn older to defy the law some salt\nwas made in Damoh by \u201cvolunteers.\u201d\nA few ounces were sold for Rs. 266,\nalmost $100.\nIt is quite evident that Gandhi is\nunable to restrain his followers from\nthe use of violence. He must know his\npeople well enough to have realized\nthat long ago. His campaign of dis\nobedience to law and order naturally\nmakes just such situations as exist,\ninevitable. Indians, Anglo-Indians, and!\na few Englishmen who were trying to\nkeep order have been murdered. In\nTahore last week a deadly trap to\nblow up police chiefs with bombs was\ndiscovered. The daily papers give ac\ncounts of violence, which sound very\nunbecoming of a non-violent cam\npaign.\nMany, in fact I suppose it is cor\nrect to say most Mohammedans are\nindifferent to Gandhia\u2019s leadership.\nMany Hindus are not followers of his.\nMany who are followers have been ar\nrested.\nThe leader of the Hindus of Jub\nbulpore, is in the Damloh jail. These\nleaders are well cared for by Govern\nment.\nPicketing of stores selling foreign\ncloth, of some schools, of liquor shops\nand of those who work for foreigners\nor are in Government employ contin\nues in many cities. An Englistynan in\nBombay provided stools for the com\nfort of men who picketed his depart\nment store! When I was in Mainpuri,\nU. P., the Indian head master of the\nmission school for boys told me about\nthe trouble they had. School had to be\nclosed for a few days. Government\nschools in many places are being pic\nketed. Upon my return to Damoh, I\nheard that no foreign cloth is for sale\nhere. Parts of that which the shop\nkeepers had was burned in big swara\njist demonstrations, and the remaind\ner locked in boxes and sealed. Of\ncourse we can order rruaterial from\nlarger cities.\nIt is not unusual to find the stores\nclosed as an expression of disapprov\nal of some action by Government,\nSome few people favored closing all\nshops in DUmoh for three months 1\nMore sane Hindus realized that the\npoor people who have to buy food\neach day after they have earned a\nfew annas would not survive such a\nhartal (strike). We foreigners and\nmost of the Christians are financially\nable to get food to last a few weeks,\nor to order it from other cities. A\nMohatmmedan merchant in Mainpuir\ntold Miss Dennis that during the day\n\u201cvolunteers\u201d come around and tell the\nshop-keepers that they must close\nshop, otherwise their shops will be\nlotted. \u201cThen at night,\u201d said he, \u201csome\nof these same men come around and\ntell us to sell them things on the\nquiet.\u201d\nDamoh seems quiet, but I know lit\ntle about what goes on in the bazaar.\nSome men have come from other cities\nto give talks and incite the people to\nmore activity. One of these leaders\nwas arrested yesterday. In their lec-\nures they speak of running us for\neigners out of the country and of beat\ning the Indian Christians. A large\ngroup of swarajists called on the Eng\nlish police official about 7 a. Fn. a day\nor two ago.\nWe Americans, citizens of a free\ncountry, sympathize with efforts of\npeople for freedom. But many of us\ncannot justify the defiance of law and\norder, the deaths, the impatience of\nthe people, the attitude evidenced by\nmany Indians.\nThe report of the Simon Commis\nsion has been received very unfavor\nably by the majority of Indian lead\ners. The Government is considering\nways of meeting many of the demands\nof the people. A Round Table Confer\nence is planned and we hope that as\nmuch freedom will be given to the\nladians as they can safely use.\nANN MULLIN.\nROBERT RAIKES.\n(New York Times)\nHilaire Belloc in his life of Riche\nlieu, making a Plutarchian comparison\nbetween the greatness of Bismarck\nand that of Richelieu, remarks that\npermanence of achievement is perhaps\nan unjust test of greatness, but that\ninevitably we \u201cephemeral creatures,\nborn to an immortal destiny, turn to\npermanence as a measure of success.\u201d\nBy this test Robert Raikes emerges\na successful man. When he gathered\ninto si Sunday school a group of chim\nney sweeps and ragamuffins 160 years\nago h\u00ab became the founder of a\nmovement which has swept around the\nworld| He was the proprietor of' a\nleading paper of that period, but his\nlasting fame came from his interest\nin neglected boys. He had tried to im\nprove prison conditions in Gloucester\neven before Howard, but, despairing\nof reforming criminals, he turned to\nchildren. It is said that nine out of\nten boys in that part of the town were\nin jail before they were 21.\nThere are now in Sunday schools of\nthe United States alone 22,000,000\nchildren, only 3,700,000 less than the\ntotal public school population. The\ninstruction is not so systematic, thor\nough and competent as that of the\nweek-day schools; but the schools for\nreligious instruction have been in our\nown history, and still are, a mighty\nforce for good. Dr. Christian, when!\nhead of the Elmira Reformatory, re- j\nported that few young men in thatj\ninstitution were, ever connected reg-|\nularly with a Sunday school. Doubt- j\nless 'more is due to the home behind\nthe Sunday school, but at any rate the j\nschool has a share in the credit.\nThere has recently been organized a\nNational Co.mmission on Crime Pre\nvention Through Moral and Religious\nEducation, its main objective being\n\u201ct oextend moral and religious educa\ntion through every possible agency to\nall neglected youth in America grow\ning up without such training.\u201d That\npurpose is almost identical with the\none that led Robert Raikes to open\nthe first Sunday school. Among his\nreasons for religious instruction of\nchildren were these: that the child\u2019s\nmind can best be worked at a profit\nbetween the ages of 6 and 2; that vice\nin the child is only an imitation of\nfamiliar sights and sounds; that good\nI seed cannot be planted too early; that\nhappiness greatly depends on promot\n1 ing the happiness of others, and that\none must begin with the child. This\nis singularly like the advice of mod\nern pedagory\u2014save that it would be\ngin even earlier.\nMany others doubtless attempted\nlike teaching of neglected children,\nbut Robert Raikes, the editor, was!\nable after a successful experience of a j\nfew years to bring its methods to wid- j\ner notice and use. It was not long be-I\nfore a Sunday School Society was or\nganized to establish school in other\nparts of England and in America, un- l\ntil the King was \u201cpraying that every,\nchild in the Empire might be so\ntaught\u201d and until sovereigns and I\nsavants from other lands were making\ninquiries about his little school in'\nGloucester. It is a tribute to the worth\nof his idea that the world is celebrat-!\ning the one hundred and fiftieth anni-\nversary by trying to improve methods\nof instruction, realizing that \u201cno sys\ntem of education is satisfactory or\ncomplete that does not place moral\nand spiritual culture at the head.\u201d\nOUR POPULATION. I\nVirginia\u2019s 1930 population of 2,\n428,079 indicates an increase of 4.7,\nfor the last decade. It is less than the\nincrease for her neighbors and less\nthan had been anticipated. Maryland\nto the north showed an increase of\nrrtore than twelve per cent, North Car\nolina to the south an increase of ap\nproximately 24 per cent and West\nVirginia of more than eighteen per\ncent. The increase for the state was\nconsiderably less than that for the na\ntion at large.\nVirginia holds her old position of\ntwentieth among the States in popu\nlation, but the showing is distinctly\ndisappointing, and many are the spe\nculations as to the significance of the\nfigures. On all sides the reasons for\nthe state\u2019s failure to grow much more\nthan would be accounted for by the\nnormal increase due to the excess of\nbirths ever deaths are being sought\nwithout any definite answer being re\nceived. There is an answer, of course,\nbut with figures and information now\navailable it is not likely that it will\nbe found. Anything like certain ex\nplanation must wait on further infor\nmation permitting closes analysis.\nThe chief puzzle is that in a state\nwhich has grown industrially as Vir\nginia has grown there is no reflection\n>f that growth in population figures.\nMany new industries have come to,\nVirginia. The cold record shows that,\nand the fact is reflected in tax figures\nand in industrial wealth statistics. Yet\nthe population of the state is almost\nat the same figure as in 1920, aftei\nnormal increase is edducted. In the\nbsencc of detailed information, as\nlias been sa d, it will not do to be sure\nof any reason, but one possible ex\nplanation and the News believes the\nfacts will bear it out in the end, is\nto be found in the shift of population\nfrom rural to urban centers. In other\nwords the new industries have been\nmanned, not by imported, but by na\ntive labor. The population of those\nplaces boasting new industres has\nbeen increiased, not at the expense of\nother states and not through immi\ngration from abroad, as is the case in\nsome of the states showing rapid po\npulation growth, but at the expense of\nthe farms. Virginians are leaving the\nplow for thd shuttle and the forge.\u2014\nLynchburg News.\nTECH MENTOR IRRIGATES GRID\nIRON TO 8AVE GRASS.\nBlacksburg, July 28.\u2014Modern fam\ning methods as taught to 4-H boys and\ngirls have been adopted by C. P. \u201cSal\nly\" Miles, director of athletics at Vir\nginia Polytechnic Institute, in an ef\nfort to save the grass on the football\nfields which1 had been greatly damag\ned by the prolonged drouth*\nLast week when the 4-H club mem\nbers were here J. A. Waller, agricul\ntural engineer, istalled a ram to con\nvey water from Strubbles Creek to\nthe garden of Pro'f. T. B. Hutcheson in\norder to show what can be done with\nm o d e r n agricultural engineering\nmethods.\nSo successful was this demonstra\ntion that Saturday a tractor was in\nstalled to pump water from the same\ncreek on to the freshman, football\nfield which was built last year and\nthe main playing field in Miles sta\ndium. Since the drouth became serious\nseveral weeks ago, college and Blacks\nburg authorities have requested resi\ndents to refrain from watering gar\ndens, lawns and washing automobiles\nI in order to protect the present water\nI supply.\nj Modern irrigation methods may\nsave the grass for use of Tech\u2019s foot\nball warriors this fall.\nSquire 'Perkins\u2014Nell, after I die I\ntfish you would marry Deacon Brown.\nNell\u2014Why so, Hiram?\nfquire\u2014Well, the deacon trimtraed\nme on a horse trade once.\nSHEEP FOR SALEE\nI have 41 black face Hampshire\newes, 3 years old, for sale, 16 yearl\nings, cross Southdown and Hamps\nhire. 2 registered Southdown bucks,\nbought in Wisconsin. Will sell at re\nasonable prices. 8\u20143t\nJ. H. NIPPER\nCedar Bluff, Va.\nPIGS FOR SALE\u20142 months old\npigs, $5.00 each.\u2014C. K. HALL, Nor.\nTazewell, Va. 7-25-2t\nCHEVROLET ANNOUNCES\nDE LUXE\nWIRE WHEELS\nat no extra cost\nChevrolet again adds extra value to the Chev\nrolet Six! Those who prefer may now have\nany passenger model equipped with beautiful\nde luxe wire wheels\u2014at no additional cost!\nDesigned especially for Chevrolet, these wheels\nincorporate many important features that\nhave won favor on cars much higher in price.\nThe ornamental hub caps are unusually\nlarge, and are finished in sparkling chromium\nplate. The bolts that hold the wheel in place\nare located inside the hub\u2014thus assuring a\nsmarter, more clean-cut appearance. The\nspokes are short and sturdy\u2014the wheel con\nstruction is extremely rugged. Moreover,\nthere is an unusually large number of spokes\n\u2014for extra strength and durability!\nA variety of attractive\nnew colore\nIn addition to this de luxe wire wheel equip*\nment, Chevrolet now makes available a wide\nchoice of new color combinations on all models\n\u2014colors that are rich and distinctive.\nYou are invited to come in-NOW\u2014and\nattend the first showing of six cylinder\nChevrolet models with thjese striking new\ncolors and wire wheels.\nSport Roadster_IJjJ\nCoach.1565\nCoupe.$565\nSport Coupe.$655\nClub Sedan. .$665\nSedan.$675\nSpecial Sedan.$725\n(6 wire wheels standard\non Special Sedan)\nROADSTER or PHAETON\n\u2022495\nSedan Delivery.9595\nLight Delivery\nCh*wU.9365\nRoadster Delivery.. 9449\n(Pick-up bo* extra)\n114 Ton Chassis_9520\nWith Cab.9625\nPrice9 o. b.\nPUnt, Mich. Special\nequipment eatra\n3\nWalker Chevrolet Sales\nTazewell Richlands\nSIX-CYLINDER SMOOTHNESS AT L O W COST","height":"26444","width":"19372"}}
